03450nmm a2200505Ia 9780520919853DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209198537 a10.1525/97805209198532doi  a(DE-B1597)543221  a(OCoLC)1163878741  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHB3631b.K58 1998eb 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a363.9/094982211 aKligman, Gail, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of Duplicity :bControlling Reproduction in Ceausescu’s Romania /cGail Kligman.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (350 p.) :b13 photographs, 9 figs., 12 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe political hypocrisy and personal horrors of one of the most repressive anti-abortion regimes in history came to the world's attention soon after the fall of Romanian dictator Nicolae Ceausescu. Photographs of orphans with vacant eyes, sad faces, and wasted bodies circled the globe, as did alarming maternal mortality statistics and heart-breaking details of a devastating infant AIDS epidemic. Gail Kligman's chilling ethnography—of the state and of the politics of reproduction—is the first in-depth examination of this extreme case of political intervention into the most intimate aspects of everyday life.Ceausescu's reproductive policies, among which the banning of abortion was central, affected the physical and emotional well-being not only of individual men, women, children, and families but also of society as a whole. Sexuality, intimacy, and fertility control were fraught with fear, which permeated daily life and took a heavy moral toll as lying and dissimulation transformed both individuals and the state. This powerful study is based on moving interviews with women and physicians as well as on documentary and archival material. In addition to discussing the social implications and human costs of restrictive reproductive legislation, Kligman explores the means by which reproductive issues become embedded in national and international agendas. She concludes with a review of the lessons the rest of the world can learn from Romania's tragic experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBirth controlxMoral and ethical aspectsxRomania. 0aBirth controlxMoral and ethical aspectszRomania. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919853?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919853423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919853/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles